{"key":"post-12588213","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12588213</id>\n<content>Of course that's not the only way.&amp;nbsp; I pasteurize straw for my farm in 55 gallon drums of water, heated with propane.&amp;nbsp; For small quantities, using jars or spawn bags in a pot of hot/boiling water is MUCH faster than an oven and gets even pasteurization.&amp;nbsp; Don't allow the temperature in the center of the substrate to exceed 160F during pasteurization, or keep it there longer than 90 minutes.&amp;nbsp; The most common new grower mistake in pasteurizing is overheating, or past the correct time, which destroys beneficial microbes, giving molds the upper hand.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12588229</next>\n<prev>12588184</prev>\n<first>12581116</first>\n<last>12588229</last>\n<when>1274233544</when>\n<utime>05/19/10 04:45 AM</utime>\n</post>"}